I’ve had SO many parents reach out to me asking for help for their overweight child. They want to know what to do to change their child’s health. Let’s start with what NOT to do. Do not point out their weight. Do not shame them. Do not feed them differently than your other children. Do NOT put them on a “diet”. Overweight children are very aware of their bodies, they don’t need you to tell them. They are also often dealing with insecurities they aren’t sharing with you. Begin by LOVING THEM exactly as they are. Begin by setting a healthy example in your own choices. Prepare healthy food for the whole family. Go on walks as a family. Practice a healthy lifestyle and lead by example. Above all, assure them often of your unconditional love for them, exactly as they are today. Shame does not produce change. Love does! 
♥️
***if you are looking for more support for yourself or your family, I offer 1:1 coaching calls. DM me!***

Co-Parenting well at Christmas can be challenging. Expectations and traditions from the years you were together can get complicated, and the shared time when your child isn’t with you can feel extra empty. This is our 4th Christmas post-divorce, and I’m happy to say it’s our best co-parenting Christmas yet. Judah awoke to our stockings missing, and instead found this letter from Santa tacked to our mantle (Swipe for the letter). My ex came over late last night after Judah was asleep and picked up the presents and our stockings. This morning we are heading to his house (our old house) to celebrate, just the 3 of us. Just like old times. Well… almost. Close enough to give our son the kind of Christmas morning he longs for. One with peace and joy and twinkling lights. One with both of his parents present. I’m so proud of us. 
Whatever your family looks like this year, may your day be Merry and Bright! ✨🎄✨

Judah called it a “rebirth.” He said in some video games, when you die, you can restart where you left off and try again, but this time you’re playing with all the knowledge you gained from your past failures. I love that.

It’s a very rare thing in real life to have a second chance. So many people I’ve loved have slipped through my fingers for a variety of reasons. Most of the time, when it’s over… it’s over for good. But once in awhile, you get a second chance to get it right. 

I’m so thankful for our second chance. For our rebirth. 
For the opportunity to apply what we’ve learned and move forward together. 

Happy birthday @sinisterrose27 
Thank you for doing life with me.
Thank you for loving me so well.
Thank you for leveling up with me. 
Thank you for holding me like I’m your most precious treasure. 

We’ve been through the fire and we made it out the other side, stronger than ever. I’m looking forward to all the adventures this life has in store for us. Here’s to our rebirth. 

I love you so much!

BEFORE YOU UNFOLLOW ME… 
Maybe you think you know me. Maybe you’ve followed me for years, watched my son grow up. Maybe you read my posts gushing over my husband and my sweet little family, and shared my shock and sadness as I was going through a very unexpected divorce. If you’ve been with me through all of it, from the deepest places of my soul, THANK YOU. And if you’re reading this now, you’ve stuck around as I have made the decision to share more than just my health journey, and to be more open with you about my perspective on this country and the world. Many have unfollowed. Every time I share my opinion on something even remotely controversial, I lose hundreds of followers. I expect it will happen again with this post, and that’s fine with me. But I’d like to tell you a little bit about my background before you jump to any conclusions about me. 

I was raised in a conservative Christian home with bibles on the table and rifles in the closet. My Dad had two dogs, a truck, and a big American flag on the front of the house. There was hunting and fishing and church and prayer. God and family was about all that mattered. We learned to swim in the river and I could gut a fish and paddle a canoe by myself by the time I was 8. We camped every summer, and Dad would play guitar while we sang around the fire. My parents have been married for 48 years. 

Why am I sharing all this? 

To let you know that my progressive liberal ass understands family values very well. I understand RESPONSIBLE and REASONABLE gun ownership, and the fact that any SANE gun owner should be willing to submit themselves to whatever wait times, permits, and background checks are necessary to keep our CHILDREN safe. 

I’m not posting because I want to debate, I’m posting because we need change. What we’re doing isn’t working, because our kids keep getting killed. Not a single American should be ok with leaving things the way they are, and just waiting for the next school shooting. I’m sickened and saddened and furious. #GunReformNow

Mother’s Day can be a tough one. There were five years of my life that we were desperately trying to become parents. It felt like everyone around us was pregnant and I felt like my body was failing me. I am overwhelmingly thankful that my miracle boy finally came. He’s my greatest gift. We lost four more pregnancies after him. 10 years of my life were spent trying to become a mother. I have never forgotten the crushing heartache of those dark years of infertility. On days like today, my heart and my love are with all the mommas whose miracle hasn’t come yet, and all the mommas who have lost pregnancies, babies, and children, and all the women whose life path didn’t go the way they hoped. Today can be hard. You are loved and you are not alone. 🩷
The world stood still that day. 🩵

4 years ago today, my entire world came crashing down when my husband told me he was leaving me. I thought my life was over. I couldn’t imagine ever finding love again, or feeling happy again, or having true peace again. It was a long road filled with anxiety and tears and loneliness and anger. But the sun kept rising  whether I wanted it to or not. Little by little, my joy came back. And before I knew it, I was in love again. Love is messy and beautiful and hard and vibrant… and I wouldn’t change a thing. At this moment, 4 years after the worst day of my life, I am loved more deeply and fully and completely than I have ever been in my life. Harrison, you are the love I never thought I’d find. I wasn’t looking and I wasn’t ready, but look where we are today. Thank you for being my best friend.  So many adventures, so many more to come!

18 years ago today, I got married. But not to this man. This morning, Facebook slapped me in the face with a wedding photo memory, and I instantly broke down. This man did not feel threatened, he did not run away from my messy life. He just held me. He told me to let it all out, that I’m safe, I’m loved, and that he has me. I have never known a love like this, one that holds my heart with such care. We have certainly been through our share of hardship. Instead of giving up and walking away, we are facing our challenges together. We are closer than we’ve ever been. Today, on what would have been my 18th wedding anniversary, I am loved more deeply and accepted more completely than I have ever been. By THIS man. 
.

Please remember that sometimes what feels like the worst thing that has ever happened to you ends up being a redirection to your best, most abundant life. An ending is an opportunity for a new beginning.

In the hours, days, months following the end of my marriage, I felt completely broken and weak. I was absolutely terrified. I didn’t know how I’d move forward alone, or if my son’s heart would ever recover. I didn’t know how I’d support myself and my son. I didn’t know where we would live or if I could ever be happy again. After 15 years together, I didn’t think I could love anyone else as much as I loved him. 

I was wrong about all of it. 

The process of recovery and healing, and rebuilding my life as a single woman, taught me exactly how strong I am and to never doubt my resilience again.

Something really special happened yesterday…. Something I’m deeply thankful for. All of my pics are candids and none of them are great, but here is my proof that it happened. This Thanksgiving, our table included my parents, my brother, my boyfriend, and my ex husband. My son (at the kid’s table with his cousins) got to spend his Thanksgiving with both of his parents, and the other important adults in his life. I have hoped for this for years. I’m so proud of us. ❤️

In my genuinely humble opinion, I believe this is the single most important change we can make as parents to ensure a lifelong healthy relationship with our kids. Be open to hearing how you’ve hurt them. Apologize sincerely and do the work to change. Thank them for being brave and vulnerable, and for trusting you with their hurts. Show them with your actions and your responses that you value their experience and insight. Children are incredibly wise and honest. When given a safe place to share, they will be your greatest teachers. 💜

This quote came out of a client call today. We were talking about her knees, and the importance of stretching, massage, and ice when introducing or increasing exercise. But as soon as I spoke these words, they resonated for me on a deeper level as well. Everything that hurts is attached to something that needs attention. Just like physical pain is our body’s way of alerting us to an issue that needs treatment, emotional triggers alert us to the deeper hurts and traumas within us that need healing. Give them the love, attention, and tender treatment they deserve. 

❤️‍🩹❤️‍🩹❤️‍🩹

If you need support with that process, please DM me, I’d love to connect with you! I am now a fully certified life coach accepting new clients, specializing in the areas of healthy relationships, processing separation and divorce, fertility challenges, parenting and coparenting, and building healthy habits, just to name a few.
♥️ 
Many happy client references available on request

Yesterday was a hard day. One of those days with high highs and low lows of emotions. It had moments of vulnerability and intimacy where I felt safe and loved, and moments of harsh words where I felt misunderstood and alone. I had my hopes up for something exciting, then almost immediately crashed as they were swept out from under me. It was truly a wild day. And in the middle of it all was this little one. She brought me to tears as I told her how much I loved her and she smiled back over and over again. She looks just like her Momma, whom I’ve known since she was 3. Time marches on but the love remains, growing as it rolls on like a giant snowball. I love you, Mavis. Thank you for loving me back yesterday 💕🩷✨❄️
